						               													<description>&amp;#239;&amp;#188;&amp;#164;&amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#146;&amp;#239;&amp;#188;&amp;#142;&amp;#233;&amp;#135;&amp;#142;&amp;#229;&amp;#143;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#161; (Dr. Nogucchi) &amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#169;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#143;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#159;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#144;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#161; (Dokuta no Guchi) is a game from Japan which includes a model microscope. Players use the fake microscope to study specimens, looking for the cure, the silver bullet to cure a terrible disease (the game was first published in 2017!).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players look through the microscope to identify different viruses. If a player is confident that they have the cure, they declare and gain 2 points if correct, or lose 1 pt if wrong. Other players can still find the cure and gain a point. The first to get to 5 points is the winner.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The specimens are card hexes with different combinations of microbes showing in each part. When a player peeks into the microscope, the card is rotated, so they only see a section at a time. Remember what you have seen in the scope is important to the game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There are tokens for the microbes and for coloured test tubes of drugs. Players build up a collection of drugs and bugs behind their laboratory screen. When a player is confident they have the right combo to complete the cure, they can declare.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
